         <abstract>
            <p>The author believes that the information now provided in financial reports of diversified companies is inadequate and possibly misleading. Financial reports should make the stockholders as well informed of the operations of the company as insiders. Management has resisted providing more detailed reports of its operations for a variety of reasons ranging from fear of losing their competitive stance to the difficult problem of how home office and research costs are allocated. The author recommends and defends adoption of the reporting rules as put forth by Dr. Robert K. Mautz in his recently completed report for the Financial Executives Research Foundation.</p>
          </abstract>
